  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal activity that is prohibited by law in most countries around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration.\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illicit funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure the origin of the money.\n3. **Integration**: Making the laundered money available to the criminal as apparently legitimate funds.\n\nGovernments and international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), have established stringent regulations and frameworks to combat money laundering. Financial institutions are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures, including customer due diligence, transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities to relevant authorities.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, imprisonment, and confiscation of assets. The specific laws and penalties vary by jurisdiction but universally aim to deter and punish this illegal activity.",
